nce your knowledge about the world&rsquo;s cuisines and popular culinary fusions. As you continue your tour you will have the opportunity to see the Art Deco neighborhood and the breathtaking homes built in Mediterranean and Art Deco style dating back from the early 20th century. Your next stop will have you tasting coxina&rsquo;s and bolinha de bacalhau delicacies on the famous Lincoln Road patio surrounded by samba music and pedestrian walk through. Feel the true soul of living like a Miamian. After some appetizing dishes, boost your energy with a glass of delicious Cashew Fruit juice. The foodie walk continues through Espanola way to enter Ocean Drive area &ndash; the party mecca. Here you will indulge in the works of some of the world&rsquo;s most renowned Art Deco Hotels. Another culinary delight awaits you in the Turtle Room at the Tides Hotel. The restaurant is famous for its stunning urban art and delectable world mixture and seafood influenced cuisine. The best is yet to come for all of you with a sweet tooth. Your final stop will be the world famous Italian Homemade Gelato.</p>\n<p><strong>6. Miami Art Tour (Duration: aprox. 4 hours)</strong>: Explore Miami&rsquo;s burgeoning arts scene on this guided, 4-hour tour. Visit Midtown Miami, the Miami Design District and the Wynwood Art District, stopping at several major galleries and museums to peruse the collections of modern and contemporary art. An expert arts tour guide will lead you through Miami&rsquo;s three outstanding art districts: Midtown Miami, the Miami Design District and especially the Wynwood Art District. These thriving regions feature a variety of galleries, museums and special exhibits and installations spotlighting the area&rsquo;s rising artists. In Wynwood, visit the Margulies Collection at the Warehouse, featuring contemporary and vintage photography, video and sculpture displayed in a 45,000-square-foot, retro-fitted warehouse space. Also in Wynwood, see the Rubell Family Collection, one of the biggest private contemporary art collections in North America (in a repurposed DEA warehouse). And in the Design District, stop at the de la Cruz Collection Contemporary Art Space, with works by some of the hottest names of the past decade. During the shuttle ride, pass a host of trendy boutiques and urban-chic stores that define these unique neighborhoods. Lastly, visit the famous Wynwood Walls (and Wynwood Doors), featuring the works from some of the world's greatest graffiti and street artists. Then enjoy a gourmet lunch or dinner (depending on option selected) at a celebrity restaurant like Shokudo, Joey&rsquo;s Italian Caf&eacute; or Riviera Focacceria Italiana.</p>\n<p><strong>7. Miami City Highlights (Duration: aprox. 4 hours)</strong>: the tour will begin with a drive to the heart of the Art Deco District where you&rsquo;ll be brought back to the golden age of Miami Beach with the fanciful pastel buildings with porthole windows, ship-like railings, sleek curves, glass blocks, shiny chrome and gleaming terrazzo floors. There are over 800 structures of historical significance, most built between 1923 and 1943. Next you'll cross Biscayne Bay which is the largest estuary on the coast of southeast Florida and the location of the Port of Miami. Admire the artificial and exclusive islands, dotted with luxury waterfront mansions. The causeway will take you to Downtown for a brief visit of Brickell Avenue. Known as the economic gateway of Latin America, it's also the home to&nbsp;many of Miami's most expensive apartments and condominiums. You'll see some of the iconic Miami skyscrapers, such as the Atlantis Condominium and &ldquo;Millionaires&rsquo; Row&rdquo;. The next stop is the lavish vegetation of Coconut Grove, Miami&rsquo;s original neighborhood founded in 1873 by an eclectic mix of pioneers, artists, intellectuals and adventurers. Today, stars such as Madonna, Sylvester Stallone and many others have selected this peaceful waterfront side of Miami as 