ons.</p>\n<p><strong>6. The National WWII Museum New Orleans</strong>: Witness a different side of New Orleans&rsquo;s history with a visit to the dynamic National WWII Museum. The Museum tells the story of the American Experience in the war that changed the world&mdash;why it was fought, how it was won, and what it means today&mdash;so that all generations will understand the price of freedom and be inspired by what they learn. Guaranteed to move and educate, The National WWII Museum features interactive exhibits, soaring aircraft, personal histories, and more. The heart of the Museum experience, Campaigns of Courage: European and Pacific Theaters brings visitors inside the story of how the war was won. Two immersive exhibitions&mdash;Road to Berlin: European Theater Galleries and Road to Tokyo: Pacific Theater Galleries&mdash;feature environmental exhibits that guide visitors chronologically through the narrative of each theater of combat, using a sophisticated mix of set design, narrated and environmental videos, period newsreels, interactive oral-history kiosks, personal and digital artifacts, and dynamic displays for a uniquely evocative experience.</p>\n<p><strong>7. New Orleans American Horror Story Walking Tour (Duration: aprox. 3 hours)</strong>: Explore&nbsp;the haunts of the 'exceptional young ladies' (aka witches) from&nbsp;Miss Robichaux&rsquo;s Academy on this walking tour of &ldquo;American Horror Story: Coven&rdquo; filming sites in New Orleans. Your tour guide&nbsp;will be happy to guide fans of the show to see firsthand the locations featured in the third and fourth seasons, which were filmed in the French Quarter. This one-of-a-kind tour is incredibly fun, educational and not something any fan of the series will want to miss. See for yourself thrilling and fascinating sites that you will recognise from watching one of your favourite shows. A few of the locations you will visit are:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Jackson Square: where you will learn about the history of New Orleans.</li>\n<li>The Lalaurie&rsquo;s Mansion: from a central storyline in the show; you will learn fact from fiction about Madam Lalaurie</li>\n<li>The location where Marie Laveau once lived.</li>\n<li>One of the most famous jazz venues in New Orleans.</li>\n<li>The location where Fiano and the four witches stop on their way to Pop&rsquo;s Fountain.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>8. Killers and Thrillers Tour (Duration: aprox. 2 hours):</strong> Experience the dark side of New Orleans with this haunted walking tour of the French Quarter. With your local guide, walk down dark side streets while hearing tales about the supernatural and the horrific circumstances of their deaths. Stop at some of the city's most haunted locations under cover of night, including some former brothels, the home of a famous voodoo practitioner and a bar that's rife with paranormal activity. This New Orleans ghost tour explores the darker side of human nature, departing from the French Quarter. Listen to entertaining commentary as&nbsp;you walk with your guide and hear bone-chilling&nbsp;tales of&nbsp;phantoms&nbsp;that&nbsp;haunt the city. You'll learn about&nbsp;terrifying history and horrendous actions while you explore side streets off the beaten path.&nbsp; Depending on the&nbsp;time selected, you may&nbsp;visit former brothels and bordellos where you'll hear&nbsp;about the apparitions&nbsp;left behind. See the&nbsp;house of Marie Laveau, the infamous Voodoo practitioner of New Orleans' fame.&nbsp;The&nbsp;city's&nbsp;most devastating arson fire resulted in the deaths of 32 people, leaving a&nbsp;site teeming with paranormal&nbsp;activity. You&rsquo;ll stop for a drink at the Big Easy&rsquo;s most haunted bar where you&rsquo;ll continue to hear sinister stories of the supernatural.</p>\n<p><strong>9. Jazz Brunch Buffet at the Court of Two Sisters Restaurant</strong>: No trip to New Orleans is complete without sampling authentic Creole fare and experiencing&nbsp;live jazz. Enjoy&n