206	General Information		\N	<ol>\n<li><strong>Introduction</strong></li>\n</ol>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Chicago is among the largest cities in the U.S. Famous for its bold architecture with a skyline punctuated by skyscrapers, museums dedicated to Impressionist and Post-Impressionist works of art. The city also known for having some of the best food, weekend events that include live music, theatre and comedy with energy and excitement all season. Chicago is built on the shores of greatness and is one of the most visited cities that attract many people from other towns and over the world.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<ol start="2">\n<li><strong>History of Foundation</strong></li>\n</ol>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>The largest city of the American Midwest, Chicago, Illinois, was founded in 1830 and quickly grew to become, as Carl Sandburg&rsquo;s 1916 poem put it, &ldquo;Hog Butcher, Tool Maker, Stacker of Wheat, Player with Railroads and Freight Handler to the Nation.&rdquo; Established as a water transit hub, the city evolved into an industrial metropolis, processing and transporting the raw materials of its vast hinterland.</p>\n<p>The name Chicago comes from a Miami Indian word for the wild leeks that grew on the bank of the short Chicago River. Over the centuries the Miami, Sauk, Fox and Potawatomi tribes all lived in the area. The 1673 Marquette and Jolliet expedition crossed the Great Portage between the Chicago River and the Illinois, 10 miles of flat, often waterlogged ground separating the two great water transit systems of North America, the Great Lakes and the Mississippi Valley.</p>\n<p>The first non-Indian to settle within Chicago&rsquo;s future boundaries was a Santo Domingan of mixed African and European ancestry, Jean Baptiste Point du Sable, who arrived around 1780. In 1803, the U.S. Army built Fort Dearborn on the south bank of the Chicago River. It was destroyed in an Indian raid in 1812 but rebuilt four years later.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>The 1832 Black Hawk War ended the last Native American resistance in the area. Chicago was incorporated as a town in 1833 and as a city in 1837, when its population reached 4,000. In 1848 Chicago got its first telegraph and railroad. Two innovations&mdash;grain elevators and the Board of Trade&rsquo;s wheat grading standards&mdash;quickly transformed the way crops were sold. By 1854 the city was the world&rsquo;s largest grain port and had more than 30,000 residents, many of them European immigrants.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>In October 1871, a fire destroyed one-third of Chicago and left more than 100,000 homeless. Its initial spark remains unknown (legends of Mrs. O&rsquo;Leary&rsquo;s lantern-kicking cow notwithstanding), but it was fuelled by drought, high winds and wooden buildings. The factories and railroads were largely spared, and the city rebuilt with astonishing speed.</p>\n<p>In the late 1800s Chicago grew as a national retail centre and produced a crop of brand-name business tycoons, including Philip Armour, George Pullman, Potter Palmer and Marshall Field. In 1885 Chicago gave the world its first skyscraper, the 10-story Home Insurance Building. In 1893, Chicago hosted the World&rsquo;s Columbian Exposition, which drew 20 million visitors to its &ldquo;White City&rdquo; of plaster Gilded Age buildings built on former bogland beside Chicago&rsquo;s south lakefront.</p>\n<p>The 1886 Haymarket affair, in which police fired on protesting workers (and, in the confusion following a fatal anarchist bombing, each other), ushered in an era of protest and reform for the multitudes of workers who kept Chicago&rsquo;s meatpacking, manufacturing and shipping industries running. In 1894, declining wages at the Pullman Palace Car Company factory triggered a crippling national rail union boycott. In 1906 journalist Upton Sinclair published &ldquo;The Jungle,&rdquo; a novel that exposed cruel and unsafe practices in the city&rsquo;s meatpacking industry.</p>\n<p>Nationwide social upheavals surrounding World War I brought many African-American migrants to Chicago from the South.</p>\n<p>Between 1950 and 1960 Chicago&rsquo;s population shrank for the first time in its history, as factory jobs levelled off and people moved to the suburbs. Poor neighbourhoods were razed and replaced with massive public housing that solved few of the problems of poverty and violence. Riots in 1968 gave vent to anger following the assassination of Martin Luther King Jr., a violent police response marred protests at the Democratic National Convention that year.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Despite the decrease in population, immigrants still flock to the &ldquo;windy city,&rdquo; though now from Asia and Latin America more than Europe. Chicago remains a centre of trade: Airports supplement the old rail and water transit hubs, and agricultural futures are traded electronically from the floor of its storied Mercantile Exchange.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<ol start="3">\n<li><strong>Area &amp; Population</strong></li>\n</ol>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Chicago is located in north-eastern Illinois on the southwestern shores of Lake Michigan. It is the principal city in the Chicago Metropolitan Area, situated in the Midwestern United States and the Great Lakes watersheds. The city lies besides huge freshwater Lake Michigan, and two rivers &ndash; the Chicago River in downtown and the Calumet River in the industrial far South Side &ndash; flow through Chicago.</p>\n<p>Major sections of the city include the central business district, called The Loop, and the North, the South, and West Sides. The three sides of the city are represented on the Flag of Chicago by three horizontal white stripes. The North Side is the most densely populated residential section of the city, and many high-rises are located on this side of the city along the lakefront. The South Side is the largest section of the city, encompassing roughly 60% if the city&rsquo;s land area, contains the University of Chicago and most of the facilities of the Port of Chicago.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Chicago&rsquo;s population is estimated around 2.7 million people. More than half the population of the state Illinois lives in the Chicago metropolitan area, making it one of the United States&rsquo; most densely populated major cities, and the largest city in the Great Lake Megalopolis. The racial composition of the city was 45% White ( 31.7% non-Hispanic whites), 32.9% Black of African American, 28.9% Hispanic or Latino, 5.5% Asian, 0.5% American Indian, the rest is other race or two or more races.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<ol start="4">\n<li><strong>Facts &amp; Figures</strong>\n<ul>\n<li>The name Chicago comes from the Algonquin word &ldquo;Chicagou&rdquo; or &ldquo;Shikaakwa&rdquo;, which translates to &ldquo;onion field&rdquo; or &ldquo;wild garlic&rdquo;.</li>\n<li>The Field Museum owns the world&rsquo;s most complete Tyrannosaurus Rex skeleton. Its name is Sue.</li>\n<li>The Chicago River flows backward. In the late 19<sup>th</sup> century, a reversal technique was introduced&nbsp;for sanitation reasons to divert the sewage away from Lake Michigan&rsquo;s water supply. It reversed empty into Mississippi River instead of Lake Michigan. The reversal of the river was recognized as being the largest public earth-moving project ever completed. It was also acknowledged as a great engineering achievement.</li>\n<li>In 1927, Chicago bootlegger Al Capone made nearly $60 million selling illegal hooch.</li>\n<li>Even before Capone&rsquo;s activities, the city had a reputation for crime. In 1918, over 100 waiters were arrested for poisoning stingy tippers.</li>\n<li>In 1930, the Twinkie was invented in Chicago by Chicagoan Jimmy Dewar. The original Twinkie was filled with banana cream, but during WWII, bananas became scarce and vanilla replaced it.</li>\n<li>Rebuilding after the Great Chicago Fire of 1871 was swift and legendary &ndash; rubble and ash were pushed into the lake to make new neighbourhoods.</li>\n<li>When Bavarian Anton Feuchtwanger couldn&rsquo;t convince fairgoers to eat his sausages, he served them in a bun. The hot dog was born.</li>\n<li>Tall-building construction was invented in Chicago and the city is known as the &ldquo;Home of the Skyscraper&rdquo;. It currently has four of the country&rsquo;s ten tallest buildings.</li>\n<li>Daniel Hale Williams was one of the first black physicians in the city. By 1883, he graduated with a degree in medicine from Northwestern University. In 1893, he performed the nation&rsquo;s first open heart surgery in Chicago Provident Hospital.</li>\n<li>In 1937, Chicago became the first city to established a blood bank in the United States.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ol>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<ol start="5">\n<li><strong>Weather </strong></li>\n</ol>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>The city lies within the humid continental climate zone, and experiences four distinct seasons. Summers are warm to hot and often humid, with a July average of 75.8&nbsp;&deg;F (24.3&nbsp;&deg;C). In a normal summer, temperatures can exceed 90&nbsp;&deg;F (32&nbsp;&deg;C) as many as 21&nbsp;days. Winters are cold and snowy with few sunny days, and the normal January high is just below freezing. Spring and autumn are mild seasons with low humidity. Dew point temperatures in the summer range from 55.7&nbsp;&deg;F (13.2&nbsp;&deg;C) in June to 61.7&nbsp;&deg;F (16.5&nbsp;&deg;C) in July.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<ol start="6">\n<li><strong>Transportation</strong></li>\n</ol>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Chicago is a walking city with an easy-to-navigate downtown grid. Madison Street divides the city north and south, while State Street divides it east and west. The State/Maddison intersection marks the origin of Chicago&rsquo;s address grid system. Addresses are relative to the distance from that mark, with eight blocks to every mile. So an address of 3600 North Clark means that it is 36 blocks north of Maddison.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Metra Commuter Rail: connects outlying suburbs to downtown and is an easy way to get into the heart of the city fast.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>North/Northwwest:\n<ul>\n<li>Milwaukee District North (MD-N) to Fox Lake</li>\n<li>North Central Service (NCS) to Antioch</li>\n<li>Union Pacific North (UP-N) to Kenosha</li>\n<li>Union Pacific Northwest (UP-NW) to Havard/McHenry</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>South/Southwest:\n<ul>\n<li>Heritage Corridor (HC) to Joliet</li>\n<li>Metra Electric District (ME) to University Park</li>\n<li>Rock Island District (RI) to Joliet</li>\n<li>SouthWest Service (SWS) to Manhattan</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>West\n<ul>\n<li>BNSF Railway (BNSF) to Aurora</li>\n<li>Milwaukee District West (MD-W) to Elgin</li>\n<li>Union Pacific West (UP-W) to Elburn</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Water taxis: For fast, affordable and fun connection between Chicago&rsquo;s top tourist destinations, Chicago Water Taxi by Wendella Boats and Shoreline Water Taxi are the perfect combination of sightseeing and convenient transportation. During the warm weather season, travel on these fun water rides to popular visitor sites such as Chinatown, Museum Campus, Willis Tower, Michigan Avenue, Union Station and more.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Single fare ride: $3.00 - $8.00</li>\n<li>Day Pass fare: $11.00 - $29.00</li>\n</ul>	chicago-skyline frm-Navy-Pier.jpg	\N	\N	on	1	2017-03-17 03:39:00.500615+00	2017-03-17 03:39:00.500615+00	59	1
