195	General Information		\N	<p><strong><span class="bold">1. Introduction</span></strong></p>\n<p>Washington DC has evolved into much more than the nation&rsquo;s capital, as the city is home to numerous monuments and memorials, eclectic neighbourhoods, as well as true local culinary.</p>\n<p><strong><span class="bold">2. History of Foundation</span></strong></p>\n<p>Founded on July 16, 1790, Washington, DC is unique among American cities because it was established by the Constitution of the United States to serve as the nation&rsquo;s capital. You can read the actual line at the National Archives. From its beginning, it has been embroiled in political manoeuvring, sectional conflicts and issues of race, national identity, compromise and, of course, power.<br />Like many decisions in American history, the location of the new city was to be a compromise: Alexander Hamilton and northern states wanted the new federal government to assume Revolutionary War debts, and Thomas Jefferson and southern states who wanted the capital placed in a location friendly to slave-holding agricultural interests.<br />President George Washington chose the exact site along the Potomac and Anacostia Rivers, and the city was officially founded in 1790 after both Maryland and Virginia ceded land to this new &ldquo;district,&rdquo; to be distinct and distinguished from the rest of the states. To design the city, he appointed Pierre Charles L&rsquo;Enfant, who presented a vision for a bold, modern city featuring grand boulevards (now the streets named for states) and ceremonial spaces reminiscent of another great world capital, L&rsquo;Enfant&rsquo;s native Paris. He planned a grid system, at which the centre would be the Capitol building.<br />The city only increased in size as a result of the Civil War. Slaves owned in Washington were emancipated on April 16, 1862, nine months before the Emancipation Proclamation, and it therefore became a hub for freed slaves. After, it remained a home to a significant and vibrant African American population, which included abolitionist Frederick Douglass. A substantial army was set up just to protect the capital during the war, and the federal government grew around this administration.<br />In 1901, the city proposed the McMillan Plan, which set out to fully complete L&rsquo;Enfant&rsquo;s original designs. This included a redesign and expansion of the National Mall, now the crown jewel of DC. The city continued to expand and develop during the rest of the 20th century, though it suffered riots and civil unrest in the &lsquo;60s and &lsquo;70s, and many residents left inner city areas for the suburbs. Today, these downtown areas are undergoing an urban renaissance, and many people are moving back into Washington itself.</p>\n<p><strong><span class="bold">3. Area &amp; Population</span></strong></p>\n<p>Washington, DC., is located in the mid-Atlantic region of the U.S East Coast. Due to the District of Columbia retrocession, the city has a total area of 68.34 square miles, of which 61.05 square miles is land and 7.29 square miles is water. The south bank of the Potomac River forms the District&rsquo;s border with Virginia and has two major tributaries: the Anacostia River and Rock Creek. The highest natural elevation in the District is 409 feet above sea level at Fort Reno park in upper northwest Washington. The lowest point is sea level at the Potomac River. The District has 7,464 acres of parkland, about 19% of the city&rsquo;s total area and the second-highest percentage among high-density U.S cities.</p>\n<p>The population is approximately 681, 170 in 2016, according to the U.S Census Bureau. The population of Washington DC was 48.3% Black of African American, 44.1% White (36.1% non-Hispanic White), 4.2% Asian, 0.6% American Indian or Alska Native, and 0.2% Native Hawaiian or Other Pacific Islander.</p>\n<p><strong>4. Facts &amp; Figures</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Presidential Pastimes:\n<ul>\n<li>George Washington never lived in DC. The White House was completed a year after he died and the second U.S President, John Adams, was the first to live there.</li>\n<li>George Washington was supposed to be buried at the U.S Capitol but his will stated that he wanted to be buried at his home, Mount Vernon, just outside of DC in Virginia. You can visit his home and estate and pay respect.</li>\n<li>White House has a total of 35 bathrooms</li>\n<li>The original phone number of the White House in 1878 was simply the number 1. A phone wasn&rsquo;t installed on the President&rsquo;s desk in the Oval Office until 1929.</li>\n<li>When Abraham Lincoln stayed at the Soldier&rsquo;s Home during summers, he would often commute the four miles to and from the White House on horseback.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>First Animals\n<ul>\n<li>President Theodore Roosevelt allowed his six children to brings their pets to the White House in 1901, include dogs, a small bear, a lizard, guinea pigs, a pig, a badger, a blue macaw, a garter snake, a one-legged rooster, a hyena, a barn own, a rabbit, a pony and a Baron Spreckle the hen.</li>\n<li>Calvin Coolidge ( the 30th President) also brought many dog breeds including terriers, a sheepdog, collies and chows. He also brought in cats, raccoons, a donkey, a bobcat, birds, a bear, an antelope, a wallaby, a pygmy hippo and some lion cubs.</li>\n<li>Not all animals at the White House have been pets. During WW1, Woodrow Wilson (the 28th President) bought a flock of sheep to graze on the White House lawn. Not only did it save the manpower needed for mowing the lawn, they also sold the wool to raise money for the Red Cross.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Monuments, Memorials, and Museums\n<ul>\n<li>When the Washington Monument opened in 1884, it was the tallest structure in the world, until the Eiffel Tower in Paris took the title in 1889.</li>\n<li>The DC War Memorial, which honors local residents of Washington D.C, is the only memorial dedicated to WW1 on the National Mall.</li>\n<li>The Library of Congress is the largest library in the world with more than 162 million objects in its collection. This number is constantly growing with aprox. 12,000 items added to the collections daily.</li>\n<li>The Statue of Freedom is the bronze statue on the top of the U.S Capitol dome. It looks small from afar, but it&rsquo;s moe than 19 feet tall and weighs nearly 15,000 pounds (aprox. 6,804 kilogram or 6.8 tonnes)</li>\n<li>Instead of chiseling the &ldquo;F&rdquo; in &ldquo;future&rdquo;, the letter &ldquo;E&rdquo; was mistakenly carved into Lincoln&rsquo;s second inaugural address on the north wall of the Lincoln Memorial. It has been touched up, but if you look closely, you can still see the typo</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Sports Stats\n<ul>\n<li>DC&rsquo;s first baseball team began play in 1901 as the Washington Senators but they were also commonly known at the Washington Nationals until the team moved away in 1971. There was no professional baseball in DC until 2005 when a team was moved to the city and adopted the name the Washington Nationals.</li>\n<li>The seventh inning stretch was started when President William Howard Taft (the 27th President) visited a game in Washington D.C and decided to stretch his legs in the seventh inning. Everybody assumed the president was getting up to leave so fans throughout the ballpark stood up as well out of respect, thus beginning the tradition of the seventh inning stretch.</li>\n<li>Stephen Strasburg holds the record for most strikeouts in a game by any Nationals pitcher since the franchise moved to DC, whiffing 14 Pittsburg Pirates in his professional debut on June 8, 2010.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Other fun facts\n<ul>\n<li>The Maine Avenue Fish Market has been operating nonstop since 1805, making it the oldest continuously functioning fish market in the country.</li>\n<li>The cherry blossom trees that line the Tidal Basin and have beautiful pink blooms every spring were a gift from the mayor of Tokyo in 1912.</li>\n<li>The Friendship Archway over H St. and 7th St. in Chinatown was built in 1986 to celebrate the friendship between Washington and sister city, Beijing, China.</li>\n<li>Georgetown is the oldest part of the city, dating back to 1751 &ndash; 40 years before Washington D.C was founded.</li>\n<li>D.C averages 39 inches of rainfall a year &ndash; more than Seattle!</li>\n<li>Washington D.C is a very international city, home to more than 175 embassies and international cultural centres, 15% of D.C residents speak a language other than English.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>5. Weather</strong></p>\n<p>Washington is in the northern of the humid subtropical climate zone. However, the city has a temperate maritime climate. Spring and fall are mild to warm, summers are hot and humid, while winter is chilly with annual snowfall averaging 15.5 inches. Winter temperatures average around 38 &deg;F (3.3 &deg;C) from mid-December to mid-February. Summers are hot and humid with a July daily average of 79.8 &deg;F (26.6 &deg;C) and average daily relative humidity around 66%. The combination of heat and humidity in the summer brings very frequent thunderstorms, some of which occasionally produce tornadoes in the area.</p>\n<p><strong>6. Transportation</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Rail Way:</li>\n</ul>\n<p><img src="/images/a4.png" /></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Bus Stops:</li>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp;<img src="/images/b3.png" /></p>\n<p>There are 1,500 miles (2,400km) of streets, parkways, and avenues in the District. Interstate 95 (I- 95), the nation&rsquo;s major east coast highway, bends around the District to form the eastern portion of the Capital Beltway. The interstate highways that continue into Washington, including I-66 and I-395, both terminate after entering the city.</p>	Washington DC Skyline.jpg	\N	\N	on	1	2017-03-15 02:56:00.532638+00	2017-03-15 02:56:00.532638+00	57	1
196	Attractions		\N	<p><strong>Art &amp; Culture:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>National Gallery of Art:</strong> explore a world-class art collection. Notable financier and one-time U.S Treasury Secretary Andrew Mellon offered to donate his expansive art collection to launch a national art museum that would rival those of other great cities around the world during the president Franklin Roosevelt&rsquo;s administration. Roosevelt agreed and in 1937 the National Gallery of Art was officially established. Today, the museum is home to great works like Leonardo da Vinci&rsquo;s Ginevra de Benci (the only da Vinci in the Western hemisphere), Edgar Degas&rsquo;s Little Dancer Aged 14 and Vincent van Gogh&rsquo;s Self Portrait. The museum consists of an East and West building, connected by a concourse walkway-turned-artwork with Leo Villareal&rsquo;s dynamic light sculpture Multiverse, the installation contains more than 40,000 LEDs.</li>\n<li><strong>National Museum of Women in the Arts:</strong> Founded in 1981 and opened in 1987 to redefine traditional histories of art, the National Museum of Women in the Arts is the only museum in the world solely dedicated to celebrating the diverse artistic achievements of women. The collection includes more than 4,500 objects representing the work of women from the 16<sup>th</sup> century to the present. The collection features words created by more than 1,000 artists, including Mary Cassatt, Frida Kahlo, Alma Thomas, Lee Krasner, Louise Bourgeois, Chakaika Booker and Nan Goldin, along with special collection from 18<sup>th</sup> century silver tableware and botanical prints. The museum is located at 1250 New York Avenue, NW, Washington DC., in a landmark building near the White House. It is open Monday-Saturday from 10am to 5pm.</li>\n<li><strong>The Phillips Collection:</strong> Founded by Duncan Phillips. This is an international recognized museum in Washington due to its superb collection of works of modern art. Paintings by Renoir and Rothko, Bonnard and O&rsquo;Keeffe, van Gogh and Diebenkorn are among the man stunning impressionist and modern works that fill the museum&rsquo;s distinctive building, which combines extensive new galleries with the family home of its founder. The museum&rsquo;s Center for the Study of Modern Art offers stimulating Conversations with Artists, symposia, lectures, and more, while Sunday Concerts, Phillips after 5 programs, and other events provide additional food for thought. The museum also produces a vigorous award-winning program of educational outreach that serves more than 6,000 students and teachers a year and indirectly reaches many tens of thousands more.</li>\n<li><strong>National Geographic Museum:</strong> suitable for all ages, the museum features a variety of changing exhibitions, from interactive experiences to stunning photography. Celebrating 125 years of educating people about the world, the Museum provides a unique perspective from renowned explorers, photographers, and scientists.</li>\n<li><strong>Renwick Gallery of the Smithsonian American Art Museum</strong>: home to the Smithsonian American Art Museum&rsquo;s collection of contemporary craft and decorative art, one of the finest and most extensive collection of its kind. The museum&rsquo;s home is a National Historic landmark, just steps from the White House. The Renwick exhibits the most exciting works by artists exploring traditional and innovative approaches to making, emphasizing crafts as an approach to living differently in the modern world.</li>\n<li><strong>Woolly Mammoth Theatre Company</strong>: founded in 1980 and has been bringing innovative and original plays the the local community. Woolly serves an essential &ldquo;Research and Development&rdquo; role within the American theatre and plays premiered here have gone on to productions at more than 200 theatres in 39 states and 12 countries. The New York Times, 1991, has put Woolly as a national leader in the development of new plays and longstanding acknowledgement as &ldquo;Washington&rsquo;s most daring theatre company&rdquo;. The theatre offers a beautiful 265-seat, courtyard-style theatre.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>History &amp; Heritage</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>The Washington National Cathedral: </strong>A neo-Gothic architecture that took 83 years to complete since 1097 to 1990. Carved from Indiana limestone, the structures boast a 30-story-tall central tower, an interior nine-bay nave and 231 stained-glass windows, including one embedded with a moon rock. Inside, you will find a crypt level where Helen Keller and President Woodrow Wilson are buried. On the nave level, you&rsquo;ll discover an intricately carved wooden choir area and numerous serene chapels. On the exterior, you will see 112 decorative rain spouts and carved stone creatures with the help of a map during summer months. Church services and musical performances are another way to experience the church. Sunday services are open to all, and Monday through Thursday at 5.30pm, evensong concerts fill the nave with singing.</li>\n<li><strong>National World War II Memorial:</strong> the majestic memorial honours the 16 million people who served as part of the American armed forces during the WWII, including more than 40,000 who gave the ultimate sacrifice for their country. The memorial sits along the central vista of the National Mall, at the east end of the Reflecting Pool. You will see the most striking features of the WWII Memorial, which is the Freedom Wall, where 4,048 gold stars pay tribute to American lives lost at war (each star represents 100 Americans), while dozens of battle names and military campaign destinations are also on display.</li>\n<li><strong>President Lincoln&rsquo;s Cottage:</strong> President Lincoln lived in the Cottage at the Soldier&rsquo;s Home form June &ndash; November of 1862, 1863, 1864 &ndash; totalling one quarter of his presidency. He was living here when he made nation-changing decisions about the Union, Freedom, and the Presidency, most notably the Emancipation Proclamation.</li>\n<li><strong>Library of Congress:</strong> The Library of Congress was established by an act of Congress in 1800 when President John Adams signed a bill providing for the transfer of the sea of government from Philadelphia to the new capital of Washington. The Library of Congress is the largest library in the world, with more than 162 items on aprox. 838 miles of bookshelves and about 12,000 items being added to the collections daily. It holds one of the oldest examples of printing in the world &ndash; passages from a Buddhist sutra, or discourse, printed in 770 A.D (is housed in the Library&rsquo;s Asian Division). It also holds the oldest written material, which is a cuneiform tablet dating from 2040 B.C.</li>\n<li><strong>Arlington National Cemetery:</strong> the country&rsquo;s largest military cemetery and serves as the final resting place got more than 400,000 active duty military, veterans and their immediate family from the fronts of Iraq and Afghanistan, was well was World War I &amp; II, the Korean conflicts, Vietnam, the Cold War and America&rsquo;s Civil War. You will see the Changing of the Guard ritual &ndash; an elaborate, sombre ceremony where a sentinel seamlessly takes over guard duty for previous sentinel (happens every hour from October 1<sup>st</sup> &ndash; March 31<sup>st</sup> and every half hour from April 1<sup>st</sup> &ndash; September 30<sup>th</sup>). The gravesite of president John F. Kennedy and his family is also here, where the internal flame that was lit at his funeral in November 25<sup>th</sup> 1963 stills remains today. In addition to the Kennedy family, President William Howard Taft, Senator Robert F. Kennedy, Supreme Court Justice Thurgood Marshall, world champion boxer Joe Louis, the seven Space Shuttle Challenger astronauts and the Tuskegee Airmen are also buried at Arlington National Cemetery.</li>\n<li><strong>Vietnam Veterans Memorial Walls</strong>: one of the most powerful scenes of the National Mall where it consists of three separate parts: The Three Soldiers statue, the Vietnam Women&rsquo;s Memorial and the Vietnam Veterans Memorial Wall. The wall is actually made up of two identical walls hat each stretch 246 feet and 9 inches, containing more than 58,000 names. The names are listed in chronological order based on the date of casualty, and within each day, names are shown in alphabetical order.</li>\n<li><strong>The Smithsonian National Portrait Gallery:</strong> From activists and actors to presidents and poets, the museum displays paintings, photographs and sculptures of the people that have come to define America as we know it. The Gallery&rsquo;s permanent exhibits take comprehensive looks at icons from different segment of U.S history &ndash; &ldquo;The Struggle for Justice&rdquo; focuses on Civil rights leaders, while &ldquo;Contemporary Americans&rdquo; showcases important figures from the 20<sup>th</sup> century specifically. It also houses the only complete collection of presidential portraits outside the White House. Furthermore, the Gallery shows guests the history and growth of the U.S with &ldquo;American Origins, 1600-1900&rdquo;, a series of 17 galleries arranged in chronological order so that guests can embark on a visual journey from the first days of contact between Native Americans and European explorers to the end of the Civil War.</li>\n<li><strong>Smithsonian National Postal Museum:</strong> houses a vast collection of stamps, postal artefacts and informative exhibits for all ages. From early automobiles on dirt roads, stagecoaches chugging across the country, pop-planes in the skies above or being pulled by real horsepower, you will take a walk through history and see how mail has been transported in a variety of eye-catching displays. The Postal Museum holds an atrium sporting a 90-foot-high ceiling and vital objects from the postal past. Three airmail planes hang overhead, while a stagecoach from 1851 and a 1932 Ford Model A postal truck also adorn the room. Apart from experiencing the national Philatelic Collection of more than 5.9 million items, you will also be able to discover the art of stamp making and design, as well as how to start your own collection.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Neighbourhood:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Arena Stage at the Mead Centre for American Theatre:</strong> inspired by the revitalisation of the Southwest Waterfront, a breathtaking renovation was completed in 2010, preserving the original theatre-in-the-round adding two new stages for experimental productions and theatre education. The Mead Centre encloses he stages with views of the waterfront from its floor-to-ceiling windows.</li>\n<li><strong>Main Avenue Fish Market: </strong>established in 1805, this DC landmark is the oldest continuously operating open-air seafood market in the nation. Several vendors sell prepared and raw seafood &ndash; some from floating barges.</li>\n<li><strong>Adams Morgan:</strong> is diverse and lively, one of the DC&rsquo;s hippest neighbourhoods. Visit the legendary Meskerem Ethiopian Restaurant, a long-running on 18<sup>th</sup> After dinner, take live in jazz at Madam&rsquo;s Organ and enjoy its rooftop deck during warm weather. Or reach the uppermost perch at Roofers Union, a three-level restaurant, and gaze out the Adams Morgan scene. During the day, you can take a short walk to Meridian Hill park, a beautiful unique architecture, acres of greenery, a cascading fountain and drum circles on weekends.</li>\n<li><strong>Anacostia:</strong> visit the Kenilworth Park &amp; Aquatic Gardens, the only national park devoted to cultivated water-loving plans with waterlilies, lotuses, water hyacinths, and bamboo grow in ponds. Afterwards, you can walk to the Anacostia Community Museum, where exhibitions focus on issues currently facing urban communities.</li>\n<li><strong>Capitol Hill:</strong> one of the oldest neighbourhood in the city, filled with history and can&rsquo;t-miss sites. You will see the world&rsquo;s largest Shakespeare collection at the Folger Shakespeare Library. The venue also hosts a variety of events, performances and exhibition throughout the year. The Supreme Court oral arguments are also open to the public. Seating is limited and on a first-come, first seated basis. Before a session begins, two linens form on the plaza in front of the building. One line is for visitors who want to attend an entire argument, and the second line is for those who wish to observe the Court in session only briefly. After the Court, you can walk to Eastern Market, a bustling marketplace that sells a variety of produce, prepared foods and handmade crafts. The neighbourhood is also filled with popular restaurants such as Art &amp; Soul, Charlie Palmer Steak, and Rose&rsquo;s Luxury.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Family Friendly:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Smithsonian National Zoo:</strong> located in DC&rsquo;s residential Woodley Park neighbourhood and is free. The 163-acre is home to more than 2000 animals from 400 different species and about 25 percent of them are endangered. With world-class zoologists and conservationists on staff, everyday offers an opportunity for visitors to learn even more about the National Zoo where you and your children can get up close and personal with the American farm animals at the Kid&rsquo;s Farm.</li>\n<li><strong>Sackler Gallery:</strong> explore an exhibition and create an at project to take home through the Sackler Gallery&rsquo;s Imaginasia family programming. Events include workshops designed for specific age groups (3-5, 6-12. 9-13), family festivals and summer art camps.</li>\n<li><strong>National Air and Space Museum:</strong> the museum takes you to the sky, showcasing the amazing technological achievements that have progressed aviation and space exploration throughout the last century. You can look at the 1903 Wright Flyer, run your hands over moon rock and experience everything about the world of aviation and space travel. Established in 1976, the place has educated and inspired future generations of pilots and astronauts from around the world. The museum contains the largest and most significant collection of aviation and space artefacts in the world. All components of human flight are on display, including related art and archival materials.</li>\n<li><strong>Martin Luther King Jr. Memorial:</strong> Martin Luther King, Jr. was one of the most prominent leaders of the civil rights movement in the 1960s, becoming an icon through his incredible speeches and his use of nonviolent resistance. He led the famous March on Washington in 1963, where he gave his legendary &ldquo;I Have a Dream&rdquo; speech on the steps of the Lincoln Memorial. The site was designed as a lasting tribute to Dr. King&rsquo;s legacy and will forever serve as a monument to the freedom, opportunity and justice for which he stood.</li>\n<li><strong>Tudor Place Historic House &amp; Garden:</strong> this landmark belonged to six generations of one family, descendants of Martha Washington. This is an icon of Federal-era style in a 5.5-acre garden landscape, designed by architecture William Thornton. See art, furnishings, household items, and collections, including more than 200 George and Martha Washington artefacts, accumulated over two centuries, and learn the personal and public stories that illuminate two centuries American arts, labour, politics, and technology.</li>\n<li><strong>National Museum of Natural History&rsquo;s Butterfly Pavilion:</strong> walk among living butterflies. Tuesday are free, but timed-entry tickets are required. This Smithsonian National Museum of Natural History opened in 1910 with its green dome and immense size, which contains 126 million natural science specimens and cultural artefacts inside. The museum houses to some of the most famous artefacts in the world. The Janet Annenberg Hooker Hall of Geology, Gems and Minerals has the supposedly cursed Hope Diamond on display. The David H.Koch hall of Human Origins details the story of how the human species evolved though full-size reconstructions; the exhibit features more than 285 fossils and artefacts. Other permanent exhibits include an insect zoo and The Sant Oceean Hall, which features as exact replica of a living North Atlantic right whale.</li>\n<li><strong>Washington Monument:</strong> see the city from the top at the nation&rsquo;s most recognisable structure, built to honour George Washington. Once the tallest building in the world, at just over 555 feet, the monument to America&rsquo;s first president still holds the title of world&rsquo;s tallest stone structure and obelisk. It&rsquo;s free to visit. However, tickets are required to ride the elevator up 500 feet to the observation desk. The Washington Monument has two colour because the structure was originally designed by Robert Mills, which construction beginning in 1848; then the combination of Civil War, the Know Nothing Party&rsquo;s rise to control of the Washington National Monument Society through an illegal election and lack of funding led to a halt in construction in 1854. When construction resumed in 1879, marble was used from a different quarry, and time and weather erosion have led to the difference in colour, which begins at the 150-foot mark. When taking the elevator down the monument, make sure to look for the 193 commemoratives stones lining the interior walls, which were presented by individuals, societies, States, cities and nations from around the world.</li>\n<li><strong>Albert Einstein Memorial:</strong> the memorial to Albert Einstein situated in an elm and holly grove in the southwest corner of the National Academy of Sciences&rsquo; building since April 22<sup>nd</sup> 1979, in honour of the centennial of the great scientist&rsquo;s birth. The Einstein bronze figure weighs aprox. 4 tons, is 12 feet in height. In the figure&rsquo;s left hand, the paper with mathematical equations summarising three o Einstein&rsquo;s most important scientific contributions: the photoelectric effect, the theory of general relativity, and the equivalence of energy and matter.</li>\n<li><strong>Rock Creek Park:</strong> stare up at the stars in Rock Creek Park at the partks Nature Centre and Planetarium, the only planetarium operated by the National Park Service. On Wednesdays. A special program is held for young astronomers (4pm), Saturdays and Sundays feature a seasonal night sky (1pm) and &ldquo;Exploring the Universe&rdquo; (4pm). All programs are free to attend.</li>\n</ul>	Rock Creek Park in Fall.jpg	\N	\N	on	1	2017-03-15 03:07:37.003842+00	2017-03-15 03:07:37.003842+00	57	2
199	Paradise Waikiki (Duration: approx. 5 hours 30 minutes)		\N	<p>Experience a traditional Hawaiian luau with sunset coastal views at Paradise Cove. You will have the views of downtown Honolulu, Pearl Harbor, Waikiki and Diamond Head. Then have your own choice of seeing traditional arts, crafts and games at the Hawaiian Village. After the Shower of Flowers, participate in the Hukilau on the beach and learn the net fishing techniques of old Hawaii. Following the pageantry of the Royal Court Procession and imu (earth oven) ceremony, you evening will then continue with a Hawaiian feast. Activities at the Hawaiian Village include:</p>\n<ol style="list-style-type: lower-alpha;">\n<li><strong>Arts and Crafts</strong>: The arts and crafts of old Hawaii are as beautiful as they are intricate and complex. During your visit, be sure to take part in arts and crafts demonstrations. Learn how to make a traditional Hawaiian lei or leave with a slightly more permanent memory, temporary Polynesian tattoos.</li>\n<li><strong>Hawaiian Games</strong>: In ancient Hawaii, games were created as a form of entertainment, but also to develop the skills of the warriors. Test your skills with &lsquo;O&rsquo;o ihe (Spear throwing), &lsquo;Ulu maika (Rolling stone disks) and Moa pahe&rsquo;e (Dart sliding).</li>\n<li><strong>Shower of Flowers</strong>: Imagine standing on a beautiful white sand beach gently showered by fragrant island flowers. Witness skilled tree-climbers ascend the highest of palm trees and spread the aloha of the islands with a floral cascade, making this dream-like scene into an experience you will never forget.</li>\n<li><strong>Hukilau on the Beach</strong>: You are invited to participate in the ceremonial pulling of the fish nets to the rhythms of the conch shell and Hawaiian chant.</li>\n<li><strong>Imu Ceremony</strong>: At Hawaii&rsquo;s only Imu Amphitheatre, take a seat to view the elaborate process of traditional cooking in the Hawaiian underground oven. In a ceremony following the practices and rituals of ancient times, you will see exactly how your delicious Hawaiian meal is prepared.</li>\n</ol>	maxresdefault.jpg	\N	\N	on	1	2017-03-17 03:24:07.318806+00	2017-03-17 03:24:07.318806+00	58	1
198	Entertainment		\N	<ol>\n<li><strong>Shopping</strong></li>\n</ol>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Mazza Galleries in Frienship Heights:</strong> this small mall is for luxe label lovers, big names such as Neiman Marcus and Saks Fifth Avenue, high-end costume jewellery and accessories, as well as home goods, cosmetics and eats.</li>\n<li><strong>Via Gypset:</strong> women&rsquo;s vintage boutique where you&rsquo;ll see 1960s cocktail dresses, more recent designer blouses and impressive collection of vintage jewellery. A shoe section on the first level also stars a large variety of designer and retro pairs.</li>\n<li><strong>Le Village Marche</strong>: this locally owned gift and home d&eacute;cor shop evokes Paris via its whimsical selection of vintage cookware, Eiffel Tower-theme notecards and French soap. Books, CDs and toys up the appeal, and the staffers will prettily gift wrap purchases.</li>\n<li><strong>Julia Farr</strong>: DC power women shop at this sidestreet boutique in a charming little house decked out in pale hues and shining metal for work frocks, event dresses and designer cashmere. The owner also produces her own line of clothing and stocks jewellery and accessories by local designers.</li>\n<li><strong>CityCenterDC</strong>: an expansive, mixed-use development boasting boutique after boutique beckoning shoppers. The retail destination takes up several city blocks and features big names like Gucci, Hermes, Christian Dior, Kate Spade, Burberry, Allen Edmonds and more. Whether you want to go on a shopping spree Pretty Woman-style or simply browse the latest looks, CityCenterDC welcomes locals and out of town fashion fans. It also features glittering jewellery stores like David Yurman and Alexis Bittar, French skincare shop and day spa Caudalie, and The Great Republic &ndash; a shop filled with rare, museum-quality Americana maps, books and more.</li>\n</ul>\n<ol start="2">\n<li><strong>Nightlife</strong></li>\n</ol>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Nellie&rsquo;s Sports Bar</strong>: this pioneering gay bar, one of the first to open outside of Dupont Circle, hosts all sorts of events, like trivia and drag bingo. Named for the owner&rsquo;s great-grandmother, the bar boasts dozens of TVs in the relaxed downstairs, and an upstairs patio dance floor that goes strong until close.</li>\n<li><strong>9:30 Club</strong>: a night club and concert venue located at 815 V Street NW, anchoring the eastern end of the U Street Corridor. The club hosted a lot of famous name such as the Red Hot Chili Peppers, the Beastie Boys, Bob Dylan, Adele and so much more. The club has a capacity of 1200 people. It won the Top Club awards at the 2007 through 2012 Billboard Touring Awards, except in 2008, when the award was not presented.</li>\n<li><strong>Howard Theatre</strong>: built in 1910 and added to the National Register of Historic places in 1974, the Howard Theatre has over a century of history in DC. The theatre has the ability to host private events with a wide range of unique features not offered anywhere else in Washington DC. The Howard boasts a brand-new stage artist facilities as well as a dazzling interior that pays homage to its history. In addition to flexible options, they also offer top-of-the-line production capabilities while providing the benefits of a full-service kitchen, a wide range of spirits and beverages, and a full staff of professional servers, bartenders, hosts, and managers.</li>\n<li><strong>Marvin</strong>: a Belgian/Soul Food Fusion Bistro, Lounge and Beer Garden located in the heart of U Street. It is named in honour of DC&rsquo;s prodigal son, singer Marvin Gaye. This tow stories, alfresco patio and maze of room get crowed late with patrons who flock to this well-known space.</li>\n<li><strong>U Street Music Hall</strong>: a subterranean hideaway music venue opened since 17<sup>th</sup> March 2010. It is a DJ-owned and operated basement dance club and live music venue. Its 500-people capacity room features one of the city&rsquo;s best sound systems and a 1200 square foot cork cushioned dancefloor. Prices are low, crowds are friendly and acoustic are great in a space with no attitude. The venue is simply a fantastic place to catch a show to dance.</li>\n</ul>	Washington Monument.jpg	\N	\N	on	1	2017-03-15 03:16:04.748267+00	2017-03-15 03:16:04.748267+00	57	4
86	Entertainment		\N	<p style="padding-left: 30px;"><strong>1. Nightlife</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong><em><u>CityWalk</u></em>:</strong> Since its opening in 1999, Universal Orlando&rsquo;s CityWalk has quickly risen through the ranks as one of the top nightlife attractions in all of Central Florida. Universal CityWalk&rsquo;s appeal comes from its unique blend of night-time entertainment, from shops to restaurants, a movie theatre, bars/clubs and even special events all throughout the year. From rock to jazz, there is live music each and every night at Universal CityWalk, making this one of the top live entertainment meccas in the area.</li>\n<li><strong><em><u>Hard Rock Live</u></em>:</strong> Universal&rsquo;s Hard Rock Live attracts top quality itself as it prides on being Orlando&rsquo;s &ldquo;Coliseum of Rock&rdquo;. Located in a 140,000-sqaure-foot building that also houses the Hard Rock Caf&eacute;, officially had its Grand Opening ceremony on March 12, 1999, when Elton John took to the stage to christen the venue (even though the first concert took place there nearly two months earlier). Since then, thousands of acts have made their way through the Roman Coliseum-inspired building, including national headlining acts such as 3 Doors Down and the All American Rejects.</li>\n<li><strong><em><u>Downtown Disney</u></em>:</strong> the night-time entertainment epicentre of the Walt Disney World&reg;. The most popular bar in the <strong>Downtown Disney </strong><strong>&reg;</strong> area is the Raglan Road Irish Pub. This authentic Irish pub brings guests as close as to Emerald Isles as possible with its authentic Irish dishes and furnishings inside this establishment. Another lively addition to the newly-transformed Pleasure Island is Paradiso 37, Street Foods of America. While this new waterfront restaurant might seem to be for dining only, it actually has nightly entertainment and a huge international wine bar, tequila bar and a selection of signature margaritas that make it yet another night-time hotspot in Pleasure Island!</li>\n<li><strong><em><u>Pointe Orlando</u></em>:</strong> During the day, Pointe Orlando is a quaint shopping center in the heart of Orlando&rsquo;s famous International Drive, offering everything from elegant dining opportunities to casual cuisine in addition to a diverse collection of specialty shops. But each night, Pointe Orlando turns into a pulsing nighttime destination as well, keeping visitors entertained with live music, movies and an attraction that will turn your world upside down. Pointe Orlando&rsquo;s main draw for after-hours fun comes from B.B. King&rsquo;s Blues Club, Cuba Libre Restaurant &amp; Rum Bar and the complex&rsquo;s own Regal Cinemas, complete with an IMAX Theatre.</li>\n<li><strong><em><u>House of Blues</u></em>:</strong> this multi-faceted establishment prides itself on being a place where the heart meets the soul, and with its mixture of live entertainment and dining options. This Orlando version of the <strong>House of Blues</strong><strong> &reg; </strong>lives up to the chain&rsquo;s billing as being as one of the best live music venues in the country, attracting top talent from all over the world of all genres; and with a capacity of just over 1,500, every show, regardless of the artist, becomes an intimate affair much to the delight of fans. also provides guests with more live music opportunities outside on the Front Porch Bar, where patrons can congregate with a drink and relax to acoustic performances, or inside in the Blues Kitchen. The live music in the dining area is only one reason to venture here for a meal, as the famed Cajun-inspired cuisine at the <strong>House of Blues &reg;</strong> is reason enough to visit this establishment. An array of burgers, sandwiches and main dishes like the Creole Seafood Jambalaya, Cajun Meatloaf, Fish of the Day, BBQ Basted Baby Back Ribs, New York Strip Steak are available for lunch, dinner and late-night snacking.</li>\n</ul>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;"><strong>2. Bars &amp; Lounges</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong><em><u>The Imperial at Washburn Imports</u></em>:</strong> Nestled within Washburn Imports, a home-furnishings superstore specialising in the exotically-sourced and crafted, you can enjoy a wine or microbrew as a prelude to some retail therapy, or to drown away buyer&rsquo;s remorse. The Imperial&rsquo;s location, on Orange Avenue&rsquo;s Ivanhoe Village retail strip, also means that you can explore various other dining, shopping and drinking possibilities at the start or end of your evening.</li>\n<li><strong><em><u>B&ouml;sendorfer Lounge</u></em>:</strong> Named after the eponymous grand piano &ndash; one of only a handful in the world &ndash; that resides within, and whose tinkling ivories provide the soundtrack to most evenings here, this lounge is a sexy and soulful addition to Orlando&rsquo;s nightlife. Located within the five-star luxury Grand Bohemian Hotel, the bar caters to guests and non-guests alike as a stylish haunt to catch some of Orlando&rsquo;s coolest live jazz and soul. Order a cocktail and envelop yourself in this bar&rsquo;s <em>Fabulous Baker Boys</em></li>\n<li><strong><em><u>BART</u></em>:</strong> With just as much mad zeal as Doc Brown, the eccentric scientist from the <em>Back to the Future</em> franchise (a touchstone for this bar&rsquo;s Gen X crowd), the owners of <a href="http://bartcade.com/">BART</a> are taking Orlando back to the 1980s and early 1990s, fusing IPAs and retro arcade games in one ultra-cool, throwback bar. If the constant bleeps and pings of <em>Donkey Kong</em><em> and Space Invaders</em> get too jarring, you can keep yourself intellectually stimulated by the various high art works dotted around the place.</li>\n<li><strong><em><u>Rok Room</u></em>:</strong> Orlando&rsquo;s Central Business District, encompassing everything between Orange Avenue and Church Street, is also renowned for having the largest concentration of bars in Orlando&rsquo;s downtown area. One of the newest additions to the roster (and something of a secret, located as it is in an alley behind the Antigua nightclub), Rok Room is a local hotspot making some big waves. The drinks served at their sleek all-white bar might set you back a few dollars, but on any given night expect some of Orlando&rsquo;s biggest rising DJs to drop in for a special set, aided by Rok Room&rsquo;s state-of-the-art sound and lighting system.</li>\n<li><strong><em><u>The Monkey Bar:</u></em></strong> a classic cocktail lounge with a tropical interior that stays on the right side of quirky. This bar&rsquo;s USP are their locally-renowned Martinis, which, in a move that might ruffle James Bond&rsquo;s feathers, are made using a muddle rather than by shaking or stirring. Take one out onto the terrace outside and watch the bustle below on the downtown Orlando streets.</li>\n<li><strong><em><u>Wally&rsquo;s Mills Ave. Liquors</u></em>:</strong> proudly boasts itself as a traditional neighbourhood dive bar &ndash; dark, smoke-stained, but crucially, home to some worldly bartenders who&rsquo;ll pour you some of the stiffest drinks in town. Stick around for happy hour and a $3 microbrew beer on Wednesday nights, and you&rsquo;ll get a sense as to why Wally&rsquo;s regular client&egrave;le have been coming back for more ever since it opened in 1954 in the halcyon, pre-theme park days of Orlando.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Reference:</p>\n<p><a href="http://www.visitorlando.com">http://www.visitorlando.com</a></p>	Kennedy Space Center.jpg	\N	\N	on	1	2017-02-13 00:42:19.47207+00	2017-02-13 00:42:19.47207+00	40	4
197	Gastronomy		\N	<ol>\n<li><strong>Must-taste of city</strong></li>\n</ol>\n<ul>\n<li>Fried chicken</li>\n<li>Boundin blanc</li>\n<li>Duck fat fries</li>\n<li>Maitake mushroom tacos</li>\n<li>Torchon of white mushroom</li>\n<li>Ampalya (a melon dish cooked with salt, then toasted with tomatoes, red onions, shallots and ginger)</li>\n<li>Khachapuri (a cheese-filled bread coated in an organic egg and butter)</li>\n</ul>\n<ol start="2">\n<li><strong>The local restaurants</strong>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Pearl Dive Oyster Palace</strong>: boasts a Gulf-style bar and a dedicated fishmonger. Devotedly serving sustainable American seafood, chef Jeff Black serves highly select oysters, as well as gumbos, po&rsquo;boys, grilled fish and duck confit.</li>\n<li><strong>B Too</strong>: a DC&rsquo;s major contemporary Belgian restaurant with a roaring bar scene and a Josper oven-a Spanish machine that achieves exceptionally high heat to caramelise the exterior of a bone-in ribeye for two. There are expected dishes like endive salads, mountains of mussels, plenty of frites, and waffle stuffed with mussels and herbs. The Chef Bart Vandaele was knighted in his native Belgium for services to the crown.</li>\n<li><strong>Dolcezza</strong>: this local treatery is a caf&eacute; serving fine coffee and gelato in the spirit of an old-fashioned parlour. Dolcezza pours Stumptown coffee and scoops Argentinean-style gelato made right here in Northeast DC from locally sourced ingredients.</li>\n<li><strong>Birch &amp; Barley</strong>: a bit rustic look but romantic atmosphere with low-lit dining room is abuzz with hip Washingtonians who come for hand-cut pasta, grilled local lamb and seasonal veggies. It was voted by Food + Wines as one of the country&rsquo;s top sommeliers.</li>\n<li><strong>Doi Moi</strong>: a minimalist, uber-modernist white dining room punched up with bursts of neon drive you the message that this is Vietnamese cooking but with a unique and creative twist of Southeast Asian cuisine. Chef Haider Karoum won the Restaurant Association of Metropolitan Washington&rsquo;s highest accolade in 2014, the RAMMY for outstanding chef.</li>\n<li><strong>Kapnos</strong>: Tof Chef alum Mike Isabella fuels his passion for Mediterranean fare at this two-in-one spot. By day is a next door sandwich shop serving true-blue Jersey-style hoagies stuffed with the flavours of the Eastern med, from roast lamb to roast cauliflower. By night, the focus moves to a Greek fare serving bowls of fresh, creamy hummus, bricks of feta and carnivorous treats such as lamb, chicken; and occasional goat or rabbit are spit-roasted in plain view of the open dining area. (Kapnos means &ldquo;smoke&rdquo; in Greek)</li>\n<li><strong>Le Diplomate</strong>: is a France-meet-DC restaurant with part brasserie, part caf&eacute; and part bistro. Brown butter-infused trout almandine and perfectly cooked steak au poivre alongside with chilled oysters and a famed roast chicken and ever-munchable pommes frites.</li>\n<li><strong>Mason &amp; Rook</strong>: explorers, food lovers, oenophiles and nigh owls, Kimpton&rsquo;s latest boutique hotel, Mason &amp; Rook offers a relaxing feel away from the hustle and bustle of 14<sup>th</sup> It ensuites with stylish rooms and great bar slinging classic craft cocktails and some crave-worthy culinary finds.</li>\n<li><strong>Bar Pilar</strong>: a wonderland of shimmering chandeliers, gilded d&eacute;cor and exposed that transports quaffers to an earlier time. Cocktails are strong and meticulously poured. Splendid for a date a long then wooden bar. There are artworks covering every wall and corner. Best seat is the sole outdoor table where you can view the entire scene of the bar. Downstairs can get crowded so if you want to a bit more intimate, the upstairs would be the best choice.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ol>	Adams Morgan Neighbourhood.jpg	\N	\N	on	1	2017-03-15 03:09:04.329341+00	2017-03-15 03:09:04.329341+00	57	3
70	Entertainment		\N	<p style="padding-left: 30px;"><strong>1. Casino &amp; Entertainment within:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><em><strong>The Stratosphere Casino:</strong></em> With its over three hundred and fifty metres, the tower is considered the largest free-standing one in the United States and the second one in the Western Hemisphere. The casino-hotel is a separate building which is the tallest structure in Las Vegas. It is <strong>situated on Las Vegas Boulevard</strong><strong>, </strong>north from Las Vegas Strip. There are two observation decks on the top of the tower, four speed rides and a restaurant. The 7 400-square-metre casino offers entertainment<strong>, </strong><strong>such as slot machines, 50 different table games, over 1 500 video poker and slot machines</strong>, a sports book and a poker room.</li>\n<li><strong>Binion&rsquo;s</strong>: Binion&rsquo;s Gambling Hall &amp; Hotel, formerly known as Binion&rsquo;s Horseshoe, is one of the best casinos in Las Vegas. It is located on the Fremont Street Experience and is owned by TLC Casino Enterprises. Its name comes from its former owner, Benny Binion, whose family founded the casino-hotel in 1951. At first, the casino was in an <strong>old riverboat style, with velvet wallpaper and low ceilings</strong>. It was the very first carpeted casino and also the first one to offer comps to its customers. Binion&rsquo;s is also the place where the World Series of Poker was born and held.</li>\n<li><strong>New York &ndash; New York</strong>: located on Las Vegas Boulevard South and has a gaming space of over 7800 square metres. As its name implies, New York-New York is influenced a lot by the city of New York. The style of the building reminds of the old New York style and there are a few towers, which resemble the Empire State Building and the Chrysler Building. There are more important New York signs there, such as a lake in front of the casino, which is a representation of New York Harbour, a 45-metre-tall replica of the Statue of Liberty and also replicas of several other New York buildings, <strong>such </strong><strong>as the Whitney Museum of American Art and the Soldier and Sailors Monument</strong><strong>.</strong></li>\n<li><strong>The Mirage</strong>: one of the most impressive casino-hotels on the Las Vegas Strip. It is connected by a tram to Treasure Island, which is another casino-hotel. There is a marquee in front of the Mirage casino, which is considered the biggest free-standing marquee in the whole world. <strong>It opened in 1989 and was the first casino resort</strong> to be built with money from Wall Street junk bonds. By that time, the Mirage was the most expensive casino with a total cost of about 630 million dollars. <strong>The construction contains a lot of gold, including the windows</strong><strong>, </strong>whose golden colour is a result of the gold dust that is used in the tinting process. The casino-hotel is considered the father and founder of today&rsquo;s conception of Las Vegas.</li>\n<li><strong>Caesars Palace</strong>: one of the top ten casinos in Las Vegas, situated on the west side of the Las Vegas Strip and is owned by Caesars Entertainment Corporation. The casino has a total gaming space of about 15 500 square metres and offers a lot of facilities and entertainment. The building of Caesars Palace started in 1962, when a motel-owner, Jay Sarno, came up with a concept for an <strong>attractive resort in a Roman style</strong>. The construction serves as an entertainment venue, which <strong>can host over 4 200 people</strong>, who want to attend concerts of different famous performers, such as Celine Dion, Cher, Elton John, <strong>Luis Miguel, Sheryl Crow, Gloria Estefan</strong><strong>,</strong> Bette Midler and others. In 2009, President Barack Obama performed in a one-night show in the Colosseum, called &lsquo;A Good Fight&rsquo;.</li>\n<li><strong>Treasure Island</strong>: also referred to as &lsquo;TI&rsquo;, is a casino-hotel, situated on the Las Vegas Strip. It is connected by free tram to The Mirage casino and also by a pedestrian bridge to the Fashion Show Mall, which is a big shopping centre. The hotel is one of the best ones in Las Vegas and it has received a Four Diamond rating every year since 1999. The <strong>building of Treasure Island was completed in 1993</strong> at the cost of 450 million dollars. <strong>Treasure Island hosts the &lsquo;Mystere&rsquo; show of Cirque du Soleil</strong><strong>,</strong> which is considered the best show in Las Vegas. The pirate &lsquo;Buccaneer Bay&rsquo; show was replaced with &lsquo;Sirens&rsquo; Cove&rsquo; and &lsquo;The Sirens of TI&rsquo; in 2003. The show programmes included dancing, singing, half-naked pirates and many audio-visual effects, all of which were meant to attract adult audience. However, the show was stopped in 2013 due to construction.</li>\n<li><strong>Hard Rock</strong>: Owned and operated by Brookfield Asset Management and Warner Gaming, LLC, the 6,8-hectare property is situated on Paradise Road in Las Vegas. Its <strong>total gaming space is 2,800 square metres but gaming</strong> earns the resort only about thirty per cent of its income. Hard Rock is in contemporary chick style and it offers many facilities and ways to keep visitors entertained, such as a nightclub, cocktail lounges, many shops, six restaurants, <strong>a Tahiti-style beach, a poker room, a music venue</strong> and many more. Entertainment that the resort offers includes &lsquo;Vanity&rsquo; club, &lsquo;The Joint&rsquo;, &lsquo;Rehab&rsquo; and &lsquo;Vinyl&rsquo;. &lsquo;The Joint&rsquo; is a rock club, where many popular musicians have performed, such as Guns N Roses, The Rolling Stones, Coldplay, Alicia Keys, Oasis and others. &lsquo;Vanity&rsquo; is a nightclub which has two bars and sixty VIP booths. The attraction of the club is a cyclone chandelier above the dance floor which sprawls. &lsquo;Rehab&rsquo; is an event, which is considered the original pool party of Las Vegas. It takes place every Sunday, turning Hard Rock into an open daytime pool party. Many famous DJs play music there, such as Tiesto, Fedde Le Grand and many more.</li>\n<li><strong>Mandalay Bay:</strong> The casino has a total space of 12 500 square metres and it&rsquo;s styled in a South-East Asian theme. The resort was opened in the winter of 1996 as a Hawaiian-styled &lsquo;Project Paradise&rsquo; resort. However, two years later the resort was renovated and its name was changed to &lsquo;Mandalay Bay&rsquo;, although there isn&rsquo;t an actual bay in the capital of Burma &ndash; Mandalay. In 2003, a Convention centre was added to the resort, which was announced <strong>the fifth largest one in the United States with its 93 thousand square metres</strong>. It includes a few ballrooms with a size up to 9 000 metres. The resort has a big shopping mall, called &lsquo;Mandalay Place&rsquo;, 24 restaurants, bars and lounges, an event centre, <strong>a shark reef aquarium and a 4,5-hectare Mandalay beach</strong><strong>, </strong>which includes a wave pool, a small waterfall, three heated pools, a Lazy River water ride and a swimming pool for children.</li>\n<li><strong>The Palms</strong>: one of the most popular casinos in Las Vegas. It is located on Flamingo Road, near the Las Vegas Strip. The resort includes a 8 800-square metre casino, a Michelin-recognised restaurant, a recording studio and <strong>the </strong><strong>Pearl concert theatre that can host up to 2 500 people</strong><strong>.</strong> Made in a modern, neo-retro style, <strong>the resort is similar to Hard Rock Hotel &amp; Casino</strong><strong>,</strong> with which it competes. <strong>Developed by George Maloof in 2000</strong><strong>,</strong> the resort project was completed in September 2001 and two months later opened its doors to a huge crowd of people. The Palms has several nightclubs and lounges, some of which are situated in one of the three towers at the resort. The second tower is called &lsquo;Fantasy Tower&rsquo; and includes a two-story suite which has a basketball court. Other suits in the tower are the King Pin suite, the Barbie suite and the G suite. The casino includes all of the classic and latest table games, stylish bars and plush lounges, where you can take a break from the lively gaming spirit.</li>\n<li><strong>Bellagio:</strong> famous for its elegance and style that is inspired by the lake town of Bellagio in Italy. The casino opened in 1998 and has a <strong>total gaming space of 10 800 square metres</strong>. Bellagio offers many facilities and is well-known for its professional poker room. Many poker experts play there, referring to the casino as &lsquo;The Office&rsquo;. The reason why they choose Bellagio is its high table limits. The casino also hosts many tournaments of the World Poker Tour. It offers a range of gaming slots, table games, a race and a sports book. The resort includes many attractions, such as the Fountain of Bellagio, which is a huge fountain with choreographed water that is set to performs to light and sounds. Bellagio also contains several restaurants and bars, a conservatory, botanical gardens and a gallery of fine art, which offers exhibitions of works of fine art.</li>\n</ul>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;"><strong>2. Clubs &amp; Lounges</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><em><strong>LAX</strong></em><em>: </em>at the Luxor offers two stories of nightlife options, blending both modern design with flourishes reminiscent of classic Hollywood. Although the trend in nightlife lately has been toward having a few smaller rooms with different types of music playing, LAX is a big, two-story space for one massive party. The music here tends to be hip-hop with some top 40 mixed in for good measure.&nbsp;</li>\n<li><strong>VooDoo Rooftop Nightclub:</strong> Located on the rooftop at The Rio, Las Vegas. An unmatched view of Las Vegas -- hotels, houses, the whole thing -- surrounds the patio and on beautiful summer nights it's pretty hard to beat sitting on one of the VIP couches at the club, taking in the city. A giant, 40-ton staircase connects the 50 and 51st floors (the restaurant and lounge, respectively) and climbing it puts you face-to-face with some of the club's go-go dancers and people talking photos.</li>\n<li><strong>Chateau Nightclub &amp; Gardens</strong>: at Paris Las Vegas, evokes classic French style with a dose of modern flair throughout its two stories, offering a sophisticated and chic nightlife experience with enough variety to appeal to everyone. The venue features a high-energy nightclub. As guests enter Chateau Nightclub, they'll catch the details and design elements inspired by classic French architecture, including plenty of mirrored and polished surfaces that work well with the club lighting. The dance floor features vaulted ceilings, elegant chandeliers and an elevated DJ booth, which has an old-world style that contrasts and looks particularly cool when playing host to DJs and their turntables. The bars located throughout the expansive venue offer a variety of classic and specialty cocktails.</li>\n<li><strong>Ghostbar</strong>: Located high upon the 55th floor of the swanky Palms, this cutting edge club boasts an unbelievable view of the glittering Strip and much of the Las Vegas valley. It's an absolutely fun and super-hip place to chill in style, enjoy a cocktail and listen to some great rock and hip-hop music. The room is a model of geometry and design. It is decked out with Murano-style chandeliers, plush banquettes and porcelain tile flooring. And the savvy clientele lounging there is as cool as the decor. Ghostbar is a small, intimate club and it's immensely popular with the 20- and 30-something crowds. Get there early or buy a nightclub line pass if you don't want to wait for your chance to chill.</li>\n<li><strong>Hyde Bellagio</strong>: a sophisticated lounge vibe in the early evening with a spirited nightclub as the hours wax on. About 40 tables are designated for VIPs, creating the aura of exclusivity. A DJ in an elevated booth begins to deliver of mix of beats. Various nights feature different sounds and even some live music performances. Thus, a quiet conversation seamlessly turns to dancing, and pretty much anything goes. Hyde Bellagio has two well-stocked bars. Their drink menu is geared toward woman (with lots of fruit- and champagne-focused cocktails like the Love Unit and a Bellini cart), yet bartenders also make some classic manly drinks.</li>\n<li><strong>Cleopatra&rsquo;s Barge</strong>: at Caesars Palace, the luxurious floating lounge and bar incorporates a classic Vegas experiences in the heart of the iconic casino. This intimate lounge at Caesars Palace has been a mainstay of legendary acts as they made their way through the Vegas ranks. Located in the center of all the action, the venue is small and cozy. Surrounded by guest seating, the stage features the chic musical style of Matt Goss on Friday and Saturday evenings and other nights brings in some of the best live bands and DJs Vegas has to offer.</li>\n<li><strong>Omnia Nightclub:</strong> at Caesars Palace, a multi-level, 75,000-square-foot nightclub complete with an ultra-lounge, high energy main room and rooftop garden which features panoramic views of the Las Vegas Strip. With opulent design and interactive features, Omnia&rsquo;s distinctive elements and line-up of DJ&rsquo;s, including world renowned headliners such as Calvin Harris, Martin Garrix, NERVO and Krewella among others makes it a can&rsquo;t miss experience for those looking for high-energy excitement in Las Vegas.</li>\n<li><em><strong>Skyfall Lounge</strong></em><em>: </em>located adjacent to Rivea high atop Delano Las Vegas, offers 180-degree views of the city along with an evolving nightlife experience that gradually increases in tempo as the night progresses. The warm and inviting space makes it possible for guests to sip a glass of Champagne while watching the desert sunset or to dance the night away as DJs spin upbeat house and dance music in the vibrant space from 10 p.m. to close. The contemporary, theatre-style space, offers multiple levels creating optimal views of the sparkling Vegas skyline from every seat in the room, while an expansive outdoor patio offers a relaxing, fresh-air escape. Seating islands surrounding the centrally located dance floor create semi-private retreats for conversation and taking in unobstructed views of the Vegas skyline. Skyfall&rsquo;s cocktail program features a list of handcrafted cocktails created with artisanal liquor and spirits from the United States as well as dynamic domestic craft beers and American wine selections</li>\n<li><strong>Vanguard Lounge</strong>: with a modern decor and exotic menu of craft cocktails that evoke South Beach. Planters lining the patio give way to white, leather-seated high tops. Inside, a long, white leather sofa with matching cocktail tables leaves plenty of room to mingle or dance in front of the DJ booth. Photographs and art by Las Vegas artist Jorge Novoa adorn the walls of the 2,000-square-foot bar and lounge. Vanguard Lounge features a daily happy hour from 4 to 7pm as well as DJ's spinning Monday thru Saturday starting at 9pm.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><em>Reference:</em></p>\n<p><a href="http://www.lasvegas.com">http://www.lasvegas.com</a></p>	the_Mirage.jpg	\N	\N	on	1	2017-02-13 00:06:24.564167+00	2017-02-13 00:06:24.564167+00	36	4
